  "prompt": "Complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc).?",
  "response": "To create an **orbital diagram** for **scandium (Sc)**, which has an atomic number of **21**, you need to distribute its **21 electrons** according to the **Aufbau principle**, **Pauli exclusion principle**, and **Hund's rule**. \n\n### Steps to Determine the Orbital Diagram:\n\n1. **Determine the Electron Configuration:**\n   - **Scandium (Sc)** has an atomic number of **21**, so it has **21 electrons**.\n   - The electron configuration is: **\\[Ar\\] 3d\u00b9 4s\u00b2**\n\n2. **Fill the Electrons in Order of Increasing Energy Levels:**\n   - Electrons fill orbitals starting from the lowest energy level to higher ones: **1s**, **2s**, **2p**, **3s**, **3p**, **4s**, and then **3d**.\n\n3. **Apply Hund\u2019s Rule:**\n   - When electrons occupy degenerate orbitals (orbitals of the same energy), they fill them singly first, with parallel spins, before pairing up.\n\n### Orbital Diagram for Scandium (Sc):\n\nBelow is a text-based representation of the orbital diagram for Scandium. Each orbital is represented by a pair of arrows (\u2191 and \u2193) indicating the spin of electrons. Empty orbitals are shown with empty spaces.\n\n```\n1s  : \u2191\u2193\n2s  : \u2191\u2193\n2p  : \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193\n3s  : \u2191\u2193\n3p  : \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193\n4s  : \u2191\u2193\n3d  : \u2191  \u2b1c  \u2b1c  \u2b1c  \u2b1c\n```\n\n### Breakdown:\n\n- **1s Orbital:** 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193)\n- **2s Orbital:** 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193)\n- **2p Orbitals:** 6 electrons (\u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193)\n- **3s Orbital:** 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193)\n- **3p Orbitals:** 6 electrons (\u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193  \u2191\u2193)\n- **4s Orbital:** 2 electrons (\u2191\u2193)\n- **3d Orbitals:** 1 electron (\u2191) and 4 empty orbitals (\u2b1c)\n\n### Visual Representation:\n\n```\n1s  | \u2191\u2193\n2s  | \u2191\u2193\n2p  | \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193\n3s  | \u2191\u2193\n3p  | \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193   \u2191\u2193\n4s  | \u2191\u2193\n3d  | \u2191    \u2b1c    \u2b1c    \u2b1c    \u2b1c\n```\n\n- **\u2191** and **\u2193** represent electrons with opposite spins.\n- **\u2b1c** represents an empty orbital.\n\nThis diagram shows all **21 electrons** of scandium properly distributed across its atomic orbitals.",
